<http://story.news.yahoo.com/news?tmpl=story&cid=1508&ncid=1508&e=6&u=/afp/20050324/hl_afp/healthfluvietnam_050324151531>

Viet Nam: tests from the Chau Hoa commune in Quang Binh province all negative
-----------------------------------------------
The 1st avian influenza tests carried out on several inhabitants of a
village where residents reported an epidemic of influenza were all
negative, a doctor in central Viet Nam said. The Chau Hoa commune in
central Quang Binh province, 400 km (248 miles) south of Hanoi, is under
scrutiny, after local people reported a flu epidemic. A 5-year-old boy
there tested positive for bird flu last week [4th week March 2005].
"All tests on samples sent from Quang Binh province are negative," said Bui
Trong Chien, deputy director of the Pasteur Institute in the coastal city
of Nha Trang, 500 km north of Ho Chi Minh City. "We are still making other
tests," he said on Thursday [24 Mar 2005]. The exact number of tests was
unclear, but he said both sick patients and residents without symptoms were
examined.
A local newspaper reported Monday [21 Mar 2005] that around 200 people had
flu symptoms in the commune, a figure downplayed by several sources. The
World Health Organization initially said the cases "needed to be rapidly
and thoroughly investigated." But on Thu 24 Mar 2005, Peter Horby, a WHO
epidemiologist in the capital, Hanoi, said there was "no serious
information so far to substantiate media reports." The H5N1 virus has
killed 33 Vietnamese, 2 Cambodians and 12 Thais since 2003. Health
officials have warned of a global pandemic if the virus mutates so that it
can be easily transmitted between humans.
Bui Duc Phu, deputy director of a hospital in the central city of Hue, said
on Thu 24 Mar 2005 that a 16-month-old baby from the village was
hospitalized. "His parents said he had fever. But he does not have any
fever anymore, and we don't see any symptoms of avian influenza," he said.
The most recent avian influenza patient detected in Viet Nam was 5-year-old
boy, from the same commune, who tested positive for the H5N1 virus last
week [4th week March 2005]. His 13-year-old sister, who died in Quang Binh
hospital on 9 Mar 2005, is also a serious suspected case. She was
immediately buried by her family and could not be tested.
--
