Source: Xinhua News Agency online, Sun 27 Mar 2005 [edited]
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2005-03/27/content_2748032.htm>

Viet Nam: 5-person family in northern Viet Nam are suspected cases
-----------------------------------------------
5 people in a family from Viet Nam's northern Hai Phong city have been
hospitalized on suspicion of having contracted avian influenza H5N1 virus,
a local doctor said on Sat 26 Mar 2005. The 5-person family from the rural
district of Kien Thuy was admitted to the city-based Viet-Tiep Hospital on
Tue 22 Mar 2005, after the members of the family had breathing difficulty,
an official of the city's Department of Health said on condition of
anonymity. The family had a flock of poultry culled during a recent
outbreak of avian influenza in Hai Phong, the official said, noting that
the city has detected no new affected [outbreak foci] in its territory for
13 days. Samples from the 5 patients are being tested for H5N1. The
patients are in good health, the official said, refusing to give further
details.
Viet Nam's Health Ministry has just confirmed that a total of 28 local
people have been infected with the H5N1 virus since 26 Dec 2004, of whom 14
have died. Now, 3 local avian influenza patients are under treatment. A
5-year-old boy from central Quang Binh is receiving treatment at the
Central Hospital in central Hue city. Also, a 21-year-old man from northern
Thai Binh province and a 40-year-old woman from northern Quang Ninh
province are being treated at the Institute of Tropical Diseases in Hanoi
capital. The Hanoi-based institute is treating a 21-year-old man from
northern Thai Binh province, who still needs respiratory assistance.
To prevent spread of H5N1 virus among fowl and from poultry to people, the
ministry has asked all cities and provinces nationwide to intensify
disinfection of all poultry facilities in their territory. The nationwide
hygiene campaign will be conducted for one month starting on 1 Apr 2005.
Local People's Committees must inform every household about methods of
detecting and reporting new avian influenza outbreaks and ensure that local
residents will not slaughter and use sick fowl, the Ministry said. The
campaign and preventive measures will also be disseminated widely via mass
media.
Avian influenza has stricken a total of 35 cities and provinces of Viet Nam
since January 2005. As of Fri 25 Mar 2005, 25 localities have detected no
new affected spots for 3 weeks, meeting requirements for declaration of the
end of an outbreak. The 10 remaining localities include An Giang, Bac Lieu,
Ben Tre, Can Tho, Dong Thap, Hau Giang, Tra Vinh and Vinh Long in the
southern region, and Hai Duong and Hai Phong in the northern region, said
Viet Nam's Department of Animal Health.
